art individuals were liberated, no matter what further anguish and obstacles they faced, they realized their dream was to make aliya to Israel. They settled in the Holy Land as visionaries and pioneers to build the Jewish state, which itself was undergoing wars and difficult economic times. Their love for the Jewish homeland and their creation of families that embody children, grandchildren, and great-grandchildren nullified Hitler’s aim to annihilate the Jews.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aHolocaust survivorszIsraelvBiography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vBiography. 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)vPersonal narratives. 7aHISTORY / Holocaust.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aEastern Central Europe.  aGermany.  aHolocaust.  aIsrael.  aNazis.  aWWII.  aantisemitism.  aconflict.  ahate.  ahistory.  aliberation.  apersonal testimonies.  asurvival.  asurvivors.  atragedy.1 aDiller, Ronald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFischermann, Robert Reuven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedman Fishlovitch, Chana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMark, Mordechai, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRonen, Lilian, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSolomon Katz, Frida, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWadislavki, Miriam, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aWeiss, Rabbi Stewart M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAcademic Studies Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311068820708iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus PP Package 2020 Part 2z978311069629508